column168: SequenceEvent: Package shows several delivery scans as well as a refusal due to damage scan.  Package was found by QA in the hazmat cage.  Body appeared retaped. Packing paper was placed where there was room for a fourth.  2 of the jugs had dry liquid stains around the caps.  One was slightly less full than the others. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed into a red hazmat tote.

SequenceEvent: Package arrived in an unmarked re-pack box leaking in the Damages Area.  It was soon discovered to be a HazMat within the re-pack box.  It was then put into a red tote and HazMat bag.  It made its way to the HazMat Cage. DescribePack: For unknown reasons, the original HazMat box was inside a re-pack box.  Both boxes badly soiled from spill.  One cap was very loose within the original box.  No seals under caps.  There are plugs under caps, but they allow fluid to pass through. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: It was put into a red tote and HazMat bag before being moved to the HazMat Cage for further inspection.

column168: The tank car was reported leaking by UP yard personnel from the bottom of the car. Haz Mat Manager Tom Robinson was called for a response. Manager Robinson found the bottom outlet valve cap was loose and leaking. The bottom outlet valve cap was tightened and the leaked stopped. The bottom outlet valve was found to be defective, and the car will be transferred into another tank car at a future date. The defective car will be moved under an OTMA-3 and repaired.
RESPONDER RESPONDED TO LEAKING HAZMAT EP 155 UTILIZED DT  RS CONTAINERIZED MATERIAL BROUGHT BACK TO DMP CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED STAINED IN APPEARANCE AND EMITTING A STRONG SOLVENT ODOR BY THE THE HVD PICK-OFF ON THE PD-12. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE STOPPED AND SECURED THE CONVEYOR BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 1 METAL 1-GAL CAN WAS SLIGHTLY AJAR, CAUSING APPROX. 4 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE CARTON. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF MOLDED STYROFOAM AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: SequenceEvent: HAZMAT was discovered upstairs, on Primary 1 leaking and in opposition to orientation arrows. Upon its travel to primary1 - as opposed to being offloaded in Unload - it lost all means of adequate bracing &/or support. The spill was absorbed using absorbent pads and placed in a lined bin for QA processing. DescribePack: The HAZMAT failed traveling up to Primary 1 as it lost adequate support and ended up in opposition to orientation arrows. This repeated malalignment resulted in failure of the lid to maintain its closure and seal, hence product was permitted to escape. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin to contain drainage. The spill was cleaned with absorbent pads and processed as a damage.

column42: HYDROBROMIC ACID, WITH MORE THAN 49 PERCENT HYDROBROMIC ACID
column168: SequenceEvent: Package was loaded onto truck WA153 and placed inside the truck next to the wheel-well by package handler during sort, rather than being staged outside for the driver. Package handlers were dismissed around 8:15 as sort ended. Shortly after, the package handler trainer on Belt 1 noticed an odd smell and followed it to WA153, where the spill was found. He immediately notified us via radio and we moved to contain the spill, which had already spread to 12 nearby packages. The acid had reacted to contact with the metal and created hydrogen gas reaction (which was stopped by application of pH neutralizer), and leaked through the truck floor. ERTS was notified and a report submitted via phone. A cleanup crew was sent out to clean the truck and the spill area below it. ERTS advised that we add inert material on top of the pH neutralizer and the truck remain in place, inactive until ther cleanup crew came, as ignition could ignite the gas reacting within. DescribePack: Unknown what exactly caused the failure other than the bottle breaking inside. The bottle was secured in a specifically-molded surrounding foam about 4 inches thick, matching the total size of the fiberboard box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: pH neutralizer added to spill, packages affected placed in Hazmat plastic bags/bin and removed from area. Affected area closed off until cleanup crew arrival.

column168: FRA inspector David Schwake found tank car NATX 160162 with product visible on exterior of tank car in the area of the pressure relief device.  Based on the spill pattern, the PRD appeared to have opened and closed while in transportation.  There was signs of dried sodium hydroxide on the trailing rail car indicating the cars were moving when the released occurred.  The release likely was the result of excessive hydraulic pressure caused by train handling or a hard coupling at an unknown location.

SequenceEvent: Hazmat package was brought to HazMat for process. DescribePack: Box was crushed and 1 gallon jugs were bent causing internal leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Hazmat package was bagged and brought to hazmat for process.

SequenceEvent: The package was found actively leaking in a trailer on the unloading dock. The package was placed into a lined tote and brought back to the hazmat cage for inspection. No other packages were damaged. DescribePack: The failure occurred from a loose cap which allowed some of the liquid to leak internally, compromising the integrity of the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed into a lined tote and brought back to the hazmat cage immediately for inspection.

SequenceEvent: The cap was loose. DescribePack: the leakage was caused by a loose cap on the bottle. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: the hazmat was put in a plastic bin and put in the hazmat cage under ventilation.

SequenceEvent: Package was found wet on the unload side. We inspected package an discovered that there's loose cap at the closure area that caused the leakage. DescribePack: n/a DurationRel: 32 and MitigateEffect: n/a

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: SequenceEvent: package found at hazmat cage DescribePack: nitric acid leaked inside of package DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: package placed in lined hazmat bin at hazmat cage, CRT called to arrange for disposal of package due to noxious odors and acidic reactions
SequenceEvent: package found in the unload on its side one of the tops was loose which leaked DescribePack: loose cap which caused leakage DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: package upright
SequenceEvent: package found on its side DescribePack: loose caps DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: package placed upright

SequenceEvent: unprocessed hazmat was discovered by package handlers during inbound, who brought it to the QA cage. hazmat specialist checked the cage this afternoon and saw that the package had its certification in a side pouch and was compliant. only after processing the hazmat did the hazmat specialist notice some corroded tears and stains along one edge of the package, as they were subtle in discoloration. a quick inspection of the inside showed that the product was damaged and released, but it was a while ago, as everything was dry. hazmat admin brought the package over to the incoming damaged hazmat/LQ area and placed it in a lined tote atop the drain mats. in-house cleanup, awaiting disposition. DescribePack: one bottle leaked a small amount, either due to the cap's venting or the cap being loose. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: placed in lined tote, moved to drain mats

SequenceEvent: The hazmat had loose caps which caused the hazmat to leak. When QA got to the hazmat it was placed inside of lined tote and placed inside of the hazmat cage. DescribePack: The hazmat had loose caps which caused the hazmat to leak inside of the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: One the hazmat was located, it was placed inside of a lined tote and placed inside of the hazmat cage to prevent further leaking/contamination.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE CAME FROM LOAD SIDE WET. THE BOTTLES CAP WAS LOOSE ALLOWING LEAKAGE. SPILL WAS MINOR, ISOLATED TO PKG. PKG WAS PLACED IN A HAZMAT BAG. DescribePack: THE BOTTLES CAP WAS LOOSE DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PKG WAS PLACED IN A HAZMAT BAG.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE RECEIVED AT VSA WET. DescribePack: CARTON WET BY ONE OF THE CORNERS, LOOSE CAP WAS FOUND CAUSING THE LEAKING. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE SENDED TO HAZMAT CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

SequenceEvent: Package was unloaded from trailer and advanced onto non-compatibles belt, where it leaked. Leaking package was brought to QA cage and placed in a plastic tote. DescribePack: Bottle has loose cap, sustained compression/crushing which cause safety seal to tear open and liquid contents to be displaced (leaked). DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed in a plastic tote to prevent further release or seepage of liquid contents.

SequenceEvent: Package was brought to cage due to improper shipment papers on pkg; It was determined that the pkg was previously leaking due to discolored surface; Package was inspected & relocated to Hazmat cage in a lined Hazmat spill tote. DescribePack: Upon inspection, packaging was discolored on the top and bottom corner of one side of pkg; A faint odor was detected; 1/4 Jugs had a loose cap and had visibly lost a portion of its contents. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: All caps were insured to be tightened; pkg was placed in a lined Hazmat Spill Tote & relocated to Hazmat Cage.

SequenceEvent: Wet, Fully Regulated Hazardous package was loaded into a trailer in HAGE-219 bound for SWND-64. Package was unloaded and removed from workflow. Package was brought to a QA cage and placed in a plastic tote for inspection. DescribePack: Caps from all four inner containers are loose. Package experienced compression/crushing, causing the safety seals to break open. A small amount, approx 2-oz, was displaced (leaked) from each bottle. DurationRel: 31 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed in a plastic tote to prevent further release or seepage of hazardous liquid contents.

SequenceEvent: The package was found to be wet when attempting delivery. It was then brought back to the station for processing. DescribePack: One of the bottles had a slightly loose cap, allowing a small amount of contents to leak. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed in a plastic bag and a bin to contain the leak. The cap was secured tightly.

SequenceEvent: Pail was coming down the automated belt system when it fell off and landed on the ground.  The top was compromised allowing the liquid to start leaking out.  SDS Printed.  In house clean up.  Pail placed in salvage drum and sealed. DescribePack: Top of the pail started to leak after being dropped on the ground from belt system. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Absorbent pads used to soak up all liquid.

column168: WHILE RESPONDING TO ANOTHER LEAKING PACKAGE BY DOOR 35 AT 15:00, I NOTICED A CLASS 8 HAZMAT LAYING ON ITS SIDE ON THE DOCK OF DOOR 35. AFTER TURNING THE HAZMAT UPRIGHT, I FOUND THAT THE SIDE OF THE PACKAGE LAYING ON THE DOCK WAS WET. THE BOX APPEARED TO HAVE EXTENSIVE DAMAGE DUE TO RAIN WATER, BUT I PROCEEDED BY TREATING THE HAZMAT AS IF IT WERE LEAKING. AFTER RETURNING THE PACKAGE TO THE PSC I NOTIFIED THE DAY SORT RMP OF THE SITUATION. OPENING THE PACKAGE REVEALED THAT THE HAZMAT ALSO HAD A TRAIL OF DRIED WHITE RESIDUE ON THE INNER PACKAGING (5GAL PLASTIC CARTON) COMING FROM THE CAP. THIS INDICATED THAT THE HAZMAT HAD LEAKED IN ADDITION TO ANY RAIN WATER THAT MAY HAVE DAMAGED THE PACKAGE. DUE TO THIS, NONE OF THE PACKAGE CONTENTS WERE SALVAGEABLE. THE PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: On April 3, 2022, at 2040 ET, Landstar Inway notified ERTS of a UN1760 Corrosive liquid N.O.S. release leaking onto the concrete at Love's in Jasper TN. No other mediums were reported to be impacted. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to do a site assessment and perform clean-up of the impacted areas. At 2145 ET, Hepaco arrived onsite and advised the release outside the trailer was approximately one cup spread over a 1" by 50' area of the asphalt. No soil drains, or waterways were impacted. Hepaco entered the trailer and located the leaking tote and discovered the valve was not completely closed. Hepaco tightened the valve and secured the cap. There was minimal impact on the trailer floor, less than 1-cup. Hepaco wiped the area with absorbing pads. Added water and tested the pH, it was neutral. The crew generated one 55-gallon DF containing impacted absorbents and pads and transported it to the Hepaco's Chattanooga office for disposal.

column168: XPO Logistics -LDA reported a release of UN2922 "Rocryl 420 (HEA-LA)" from a 55 gallon metal drum that was punctured by the forklift. ERTS dispatched Lone Star Hazmat to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 0800 ET, Lone Star personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 55 gallons of product released to an 8' x 28' area of the trailer floor and a 16' x 20' area of the concrete dock floor. The damaged drum was placed into a 95 gallon poly overpack. Soda ash was then deployed to neutralize the impacted areas. Absorbents were then worked into the release and collected. All waste was collected and containerized into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: The driver knew not all product would fit in the customer tank.  When they reached the designated stop point the driver shut down the product flow by closing the valves on the trailer.  He then hooked up his air compressor line to the bleeder valve, turned on the compressor, and opened up the bleeder valve which should have injected air pressure in to the product hoses to help clear them to make it safe to disconnect.  However when he opened the bleeder valve nothing was happening.  He soon realized that he had a knot in his airline.  After he got it untangled air start blowing through the line.  He was standing near where the airline was connected to the bleeder valve and product started spraying out from that connection as the rubber grommet inside the bleeder valve was evidently worn out.  It sprayed up under his face shield and impacted his lower face (not his eyes).  He immediately ran over to the safety shower and rinses for 30 seconds.  Then he came back, shut down his compressor, waited for the product to stop spraying out from the leaky connection, then closed the bleeder valve and went back to the safety shower for 15 minutes.  We connected him with the nurse Triage team and they advised he didn't need to seek treatment unless he felt any symptoms which he did not.
column169: The grommet showed signs of aging and deterioration.  I coached the driver on checking it good before hooking up to it but admittedly its not in a great spot to easily check it.  I did however also coach the driver to ensure he is at a good angle when opening and closing valves so that his PPE takes the impact from any potential product releases.  I followed up with him the next day and confirmed he is still feeling fine.

column168: The driver was performing a pre-trip inspection and noticed that liquid was dripping from the trailer.  The trailer was placed back in the dock and it was discovered that a tote was leaking at the site of the valve.  It was discovered that the valve was stuck open but the cap was still intact.  Since the cap was still on there was little liquid that leaked out.  The tote was removed from the trailer and repackaged.
column169: Further investigation reveaied there was a leak from another tote that was located at our disposal facility.  The tote was of the same design.  It appears that the totes were received from the same requalifier and had similar issues with the piping on the bottom of the IBC not connecting properly to the valve.  All totes of this design from the requalifer have been pulled from Veolia operations. Since then we have not had issues with any other totes.

SequenceEvent: Package was found by Outbound personnel on truck #432920 (Route #645) lying on its side along with Package #272252307445. column168: CEVA Logsitcs notified ERTS of a trailer release in Valdosta, GA. It was reported that an unknown amount of oxidizer was released from a container inside trailer #MCO-0557. The cause of the release is unknown. The release impacted the trailer. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities. The environmental contractor arrived on site and advised that approximately 15 gallons of a UN2014 (ECOLAB Eco-Star Oxy-Brite) had released to an area of trailer floor and adjacent area of parking lot resulting from an apparent pinhole puncture of 1-DF.  Containment pads and had been placed by site personnel for initial containment. The environmental contractor offloaded the trailer and cleaned the impacted areas and areas of impacted parking lot. The trailer was reloaded and continued in transit. All waste was collected, containerized and taken off site for pending disposal. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by this release.

column168: On 4-12-22 at 0800 an FRA inspector stopped at MP A 840 in Auburndale, FL to inspect tank cars.  FRA inspector discovered CPDX 109068, a residue tank car of Petroleum Gases, Liquidfied (Propane) to be leaking from the vapor line. The car was isolated and Chemtrec was notified (CHEMTREC Report #2022042100104). Hulls Environmental and Hepaco LLC, a CSXT response contractors, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapors were being released from the vapor valve and secondary closure plug was less than tool tight. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Steve Baldwin with KAG Logistics, 863-209-0703. Contractor personnel closed the vapor line valve and properly tightened the vapor line valve secondary closure plug. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.
column169: (NAR code:136 5 What Failed: Air Inlet / Vapor Valve Where Failed: Closure plug Why Failed: Less than tool tight, valve open)

column168: XPO Logistics Terminal UST called to report a 275 gallon poly tote of UN3266 "Cool CIP" arrived cracked at the top releasing 2 cups of product. ERTS dispatched Patriot Environmental services to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. Patriot personnel arrived onsite and observed a 5' X 5' area impacted on the trailer yard by an estimated 1 gallon of Cool CIP from a small puncture at the bottom of the tote, the tote was flipped by terminal personnel prior to Patriots arrival. Patriot advised no other areas were impacted, the crew began to gravity feed the product into a new tote. Once complete, the damaged tote was cut up and containerized. The impacted area was cleaned with absorbents. All spent absorbents and the cut up tote were placed into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

A Veolia employee was offloading a trailer using the forklift.  The drum loader attachment on the forklift simultaneously grabs the top and bottom portion of the drum.  As the forklift operator was driving the drum suddenly fell from the forklift grabbers causing the spill.  Many drums have been moved by the forklift with this type of drum grabber in the past and there have never been any issues.  This was a reconditioned drum and may have been defective.
column169: Veolia will keep an eye on the most recent batch of reconditioned drums that were purchased for use at this facility to see if they show any signs of defects.

column168: Circle K reported that 8,400-gallons of gasoline and biodiesel fuel released from a fuel tank impacting soil and water in a drainage ditch. ERTS dispatched Environmental Works to conduct all onsite clean up operations. At 0615 ET Environmental Works personnel arrived onsite and confirmed that 8,400-gallon of gasoline a biodiesel released to a soil and drainage culvert. The Fire Department sprayed the tanker with fire foam as a safety precaution before the tanker was emptied. Environmental Works recovered 500-gallons from the tanker and placed the remaining product into two frac tanks.  The two frac tanks were staged on the service road outside of the Sunbelt facility.  A skid steer was utilized to push the fire foam off the roadway that was used by the Fire Department. Three vacuum trucks were utilized to obtain impacted liquids. 11,500-gallons of impacted water from the east, west, and median drainage ditch were recovered and staged in the frac tank. Approximately 300-500 gallons of fire foam from the median was staged in the second frac tank.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: 14 industrial forklift batteries were strapped front to back and laterally on a flatbed trailer.  The tractor trailer swerved to avoid a motorist who stopped suddnely in front of him due to a wreck on the road.  One of the batteries came loose from its strapping and fell off of the truck.  The battery tumbled down a hillside, and the 18 battery cells inside its steel tray came out of the tray and were scattered on the hillside, leaking battery electrolyte in the process.  Less than 50 gallons of electrolyte was released.  SET Environmental was engaged to clean up the spill, and was on site within 3 hours.  The battery cells were retrieved, electrolyte neutralized with soda ash, and impacted soil removed for proper disposal.  Soil was analyzed and found to be non-hazardous.  Battery cells were sent to a battery smelter for proper recycling.
column169: Transportation company stated that the batteries were properly secured for shipment but one battery came loose due to the heavy braking and maneuvering.

column168: At 0619 ET, XPO Logistics contacted ERTS to report a spill that occurred at terminal NBM in Bessemer, AL. The spill occurred on 4/27 at 20:30 PM, inside of trailer number 3158535. The spill consisted of (2) 5 gallon punctured metal pails of UN1263 Sherwin-Williams Duraspar 2K, of which around 9 gallons were released. The pails were punctured due to too much freight being placed on top of them, which caused them to leak out. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct cleanup. At 0930 ET, Hepaco arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 6 gallons of product released from 2 pails to a 4' x 4' area of the trailer floor. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and then collected. The waste was placed into (2) 55 gallon metal drums which were staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

ERTS dispatched Cleaning Guys to conduct cleanup. At 0745 ET, Cleaning Guys arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10 gallons of product released to the concrete dock and trailer floor. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected. The floors were neutralized and the damaged pails were containerized. All waste was placed into (3) 55 gallon poly drums which were staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: SequenceEvent: MY SUPERVISOR INFORMED ME THAT THERE WAS A DAMAGED HAZMAT. WE BOTH LOOKED AT IT AND DETERMINED THERE WAS A SMALL RELEASE DUE TO THE VISIBLE DAMAGE ON THE LABEL. ALSO, WHEN THE PAIL WAS LIFTED BY ITS HANDLE, WE COULD SMELL THE CHEMICAL INSIDE. AT THAT POINT I TOOK SEVERAL PICTURES AND THEN PLACED THE DAMAGED PAIL INSIDE A YELLOW SALVAGE DRUM TO CONTAIN IT. THERE WAS NO VISIBLE CHEMICAL LIQUID ON THE PAIL OR THE GROUND THAT COULD HAVE CAUSED HARM TO ANYONE.  THERE WERE NO VISIBLE PUNCTURES OR DENTS ON PAIL. DescribePack: THE RELEASE APPEARS TO BE COMING FROM THE CAP AREA. THERE ARE NO HOLES OR CRACKS ON THE PAIL THAT WAS USED TO TRANSPORT THIS CHEMICAL. THE CAP IS NOT A SCREW-ON TYPE CAP.  IT IS  A COMPRESSION TYPE CAP. IT HAS A METAL RING AND A PLASTIC COMPONENT THAT IS PULLED OUT TO RELEASE ITS CONTENTS. THE CAP CANNOT BE TIGHTENED OR LOOSENED BY HAND. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: ONCE WE REALIZED THE PAIL WAS LEAKING, I PLACED IT IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THEN SECURED IT IN THE QA HAZMAT CAGE.

column168: Driver forgot to put the loading arm over the dome area.  He hit the start button and 400 gallons spilled out on the trailer and ground in a containment area. column169: The driver has been loading at this location for some time.  He is the only Schneider driver who loads here.  This highlighted the fact that we did not have training in place for this location which may or may not have contributed to the situation.  At Schneider, anytime a driver does self loading using customer equipment it is our requirement to provide them with site specific training.  I don't think that inherently caused him to miss this so we also have him coming in for training to ensure he rechecks his processes before the point of no return.  Training has since been implemented.

column168: On 4/27/2022 at 04:00 local time in Seattle, cargo supervisor Wei-Li, Pan discovered on China Airlines flight CI5241 that there was sticky liquid on the ground and he identified the pallet of possible leakage (PMC-92641CI) which was being moved from position PR to position KR at our station (4 overpacked packages on this pallet with 4 steel drums in each package). This pallet was loaded onto the aircraft at a previous station KATL. He decided to offload the pallet at our station according to our company’s emergency procedure 8.1.1. The pallet was then being put in the backyard of Swissport warehouse. On the same day at 16:10 local time Seattle, the Swissport called the fire department to come out and only assessed whether they needed to respond, which they did not, and told Swissport to call back again if it began leaking more or actively overflowing. The cleaning company Clean Harbors arrived at Swissport at 16:35 for the clean up. They identified the leaking drums and proceeded to put the one damaged drum into another yellow drum for storage; the rest of the shipment is safely stored in the secured area inside the Swissport warehouse along with the damaged drum right now. Clean Harbors stated that “When we arrived on site all the drum were still bungee and wrapped, we removed the bungees and plastic wrap to identify the leaking drum. One drum had damage to the bottom of it that looked like damage from a drum loader or forklift forks. Approximately 5 to 10 gallons look to have leaked out of the drum”.We called the PERS 24 Hour emergency number at 801-629-0667 to report the incident and the reference number is #202204290610213. I have attached the airway bill of the shipment, along with the commercial invoice, and the cleaning report and photos of the damaged drum in this initial report.

On April 21, 2022, at 0445 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal LSL experienced an approximate 30 gallon release of UN1993 “Biobor JF” from a 55 gallon metal drum. The release impacted the trailer floor, dock, and concrete lot below due to a forklift puncture. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to conduct all on site cleanup operations. On April 21, 2022, at 0650 EST, E3 personnel arrived on site and confirmed approximately 30 gallons of product released to a 20 sq ft dock area, 8’ x 25’area in the trailer, and a 12’ x 6’ area of the concrete yard below the trailer. Absorbents were worked into all impacted areas to collect the release. The damaged drum was placed into an 85 gallon metal overpack. All spent absorbents were then collected and containerized into (2) 55 gallon metal drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: During a normal operation in the Harrison Yard bowl, Memphis TN on 25 APRIL 2022, A leak from the top of ACFX 72220 (Load, UN3082, Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, N.O.S.) has been witnessed by a CN Transportation employee. The transportation supervisor and DG officer immediately were notified. All proper notifications made. CN DG response team also observed a liquid release from the top of the car down to the underside of the tank car and onto the rungs and side rails of the ladder. All customer shipping seals were intact. Upon inspection, the manway lid gasket was discovered protruding from under the lid. After opening the lid, the manway lid gasket was found broken with a large portion of the gasket missing. The damaged gasket was removed, the lid and rim nozzle were cleaned and inspected, and a rim nozzle gasket installed. The tank car was properly secured for transportation and sealed. The car was released to transportation for movement.

Rail car was being unloaded at night. A fitting on the unloading pipeline leaked, for an estimated 2 hrs. Due to weather (raining), lighting and the location of the leak, the leak was not detected until daylight. The release was contained in the area where the fitting leaked. There was no runoff from the site. When the leak was discovered unloading operations were halted. The Indiana Department of Environmental Management was immediately notified (report #100860), and a contractor was immediately mobilized to the site and completed its cleanup largely by 4/15, with final gravel removal and replacement completed 4/23.

column168: Union Pacific reported BNSF train H-STOPVO1-20A with a leaking car (TILX 281838).  The train was inspected at Soda Springs, CA and UP Hazmat contracted Graymar Env out of Reno to respond as this occured on UP tracks/property.  Inspection revealed that the liquid line plug was out of the valve and it was in the fully open position contributing to the release.  UP contractor cleaned and secured the car for continue transport.  Environmental remediation performed by UP.  No impacts found to BNSF property.  Loss estimates are based upon information received by the shipper given outage measurements recorded during the inspection.
column169: The shipper should review post loading practices to ensure that cars are secured prior to release.(NAR:119)

column168: The UTLX 662391 was found leaking in the Globeville yard by yard crews working near Track 111.  No injuries or exposures and no waterways or drains were impacted.  The car was isolated for inspection by BNSF Hazmat responders.  Upon arrival, the responder identified all seals intact on the protective housing and found that the liquid line valve was partially opened with the plug missing.  The responder closed the valve and reinstalled the threaded plug.  HMR was contracted to clean the car and impacts to the ground.  Approx 750 gallons was released from the car and impacted three yard tracks.  MDI was solidified and removed using vacuum trucks to be placed in bins pending disposal.
column169: Review post loading procedures at origin to ensure that cars are properly secured prior to being released into transportation.(NAR:119)

column168: RNLU100335 (with Hazmat cargo declared) was reported slowly leaking a liquid along the right side of the container by a Greenwood M.L driver after deramping at the STOIMF CA hub on 4/28/22. The unit was moved to the containment pit & US Ecology began remediating the release, finding the culprit to be a pallet on 2nd layer E   track load bars, fell onto an IBC tote underneath, puncturing the plastic bladder & releasing an estimated 120 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide solution (one of the hazmat declared cargos). This release is suspected to occur in the beginning of the trip as the release was 2 drops/minute as observed at Stockton. Less than one gallon total released at STOIMF.  No securement was used on this cargo, which allowed the cargo shifting/migration.

On 4/29/2021 a 5 gallon plastic drum at the Veolia, Newington, CT 10 day intransit facility was observed to be leaking. Employees walked by the parked truck and noticed a solvent smell and a drip from the side of the truck. They inspected the truck and identified a leaking 5 gallon pail. Employees opened the back door of the truck and inspected all containers within the truck. Upon inspection it was determined that there was a 5 gallon drum that was used for liquids when it was only rated for solids. It was a "screw type" lid closure and it did not prevent the liquid contents from spilling out of it. The drum was overpacked into a suitable container for continued transportation.   The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the pail/drum was overpacked along with the clean up materials. The duration of release is anticipated to be about an hour from leaving the shipper site to the Veolia office.
column169: On 4/29/2021 the Veolia safety manager of Marlborough, MA was notified. The results of the investigation is that a drum containing liquid was incorrectly selected by customer and not caught by Veolia employee prior to shipment. This was due to human error when loading the container with the solvent.  The Veolia manager met with the employee and retrained them on preventing these pails from being used for shipping liquids in the future.

column168: The driver said he loaded the product by vacuuming it onto the trailer. He said he heard a pop and the vacuum pressure dropped to around 10 Inches of vacuum. He assumed the trailer was full and ended the loading process. After leaving the customefs facility, the driver made a tum and saw in his mirror that product had sloshed from the dome lid and was running down the side of the tank. Indiana State Police responded immediately and recommended a local towing service that the officer thought had the assets to clean up the spill on the roadway. It was later discovered that a small amount had run down the side of the roadway and gotten into a storm sewer. Veolia notified a remediation company that responded and sucked the product out of the storm drain, removed a small amount of impacted soil, and cleaned the surface of the roadway. It was determined that the gasket on the rear dome lid had failed and fallen into the tank, causing the tank to lose vacuum. When the driver made a sharp tum the product sloshed and flowed out under the dome lid. We believe the reason for the failure of the gasket was that it was not seated properly when the dome lid was closed and tightened, and it got pinched or cut.
column169: are also advising them to pull a vacuum after the loading process is complete on all vacuum trailers, and to leave a vacuum on the trailer during transport to prevent leaks in transit.

On 4/25/22 USCG conducted routine random inspection of containers at the Hawaii Stevedores cargo terminal at P-51 A Upon inspection of container HRZU454041-3 the inspectors found 6 cartons@ 49 lbs of the class 8 commodity that was not declared on the haz documents. No class 8 placards affixed to the contanier. Also 1 class 9 placard was missing. Container and shipment was detained until corrections were initiated.
column169: Shipper provided corrected documentation declaring the dass 8 hazmat Container was properly placarded on all 4 sides identifying the class 8 material. The one missing class 9 placard was also placed on to the freight container. Coast Guard inspected the updated haz doc and container and released the cargo for onward tranport to consignee by Highway on 4/27/22. column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: At 10:04 on 4/6/2022, Kansas City Southern Railway(KCS) employees working In the Mossville rail yard located in Westlake, LA reported UTLX 220566 leaking from the top of tank car. The car was isolated and the KCS Environmental& Hazmat Department mobilized a railroad qualified response contractor to investigate and mitigate the leak. The Louisiana State Police was notified (report number 22-01796).  Upon arrival, the response contractor observed that the release originated from under the sealed protective housing cover. Once the protective housing cover was opened, the responders observed that the secondary closure plugs were not installed on the liquid and vapor valves. The liquid and vapor valves were found in the closed position. The source of the release was the pipe fitting connection between the liquid valve and pipe threads. The liquid valve was rotated in clockwise direction to tighten the connection and stop the leak. The resident pressure was vented from the tank car. The spilled material was recovered for disposal and the tank car exterior and ballast section decontaminated and neutralized.   File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a 'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It Is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: 04APR2022/1950L DURING THE BUILD UP OF MAWB 369-82149723 ONE IBC WAS SLIGHTLY PUNCTURED BY PROTRUDING FORKLIFT BLADES. SEVERAL IBC WERE ALREADY LOADED ONTO THE ULD. FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING AN IBC IN FRONT OF ANOTHER IBC. THE FORKLIFT BLADES WERE PROTRUDING JUST BEYOND THE EDGE OF THE SKID OF THE IBC ON THE FORKLIFT. AS THE IBC WAS BEING POSITIONED ON THE ULD, THE PROTRUDING BLADES MADE CONTACT WITH AN IBC ALREADY LOADED, CAUSING A MINOR PUNCTURE IN THE LINER. APPROXIMATELY ONE TABLESPOON'S WORTH OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT ONTO THE FORKLIFT BLADE. DAMAGED IBC WAS COMPLETELY WRAPPED AND SECURED IN PLASTIC SHEETING, ALONG WITH SPILLED CONTENT. REPAIR CONTRACTOR CONTACTED.
column169: - FORKLIFT OPERATOR SENT FOR RE-TRAINING. - COUNSELED ENTIRE OPERATIONS TEAM ON PROPER LOAD POSITIONING ON FORKLIFTS WHEN LOADING ULDS. - EMPHASIZED THE USE OF SPOTTERS WHEN FORKLIFT OPERATOR;S VIEW IS BLOCKED.

column168: One 20 L container of Corrosive Class 8, was not Ieaking on the truck but after the forklift moved it to the location on the floor noticed it started to leak. Cubes of chemistry shifted during transportation from Europe to America. It is unknown exactly if the shifting happened on the vessel or truck. When the shipping container was opened, it was observed that some cubes of material on the bottom layer of the pallet were Ieaning off the edge of the pallet. It appeared they were not securely shrink wrapped to the pallet. The shrink wrap did not continue below the top surface of the pallet to secure the cubes to the pallet. The pallet was loaded onto a forklift and removed from the shipping container. When the pallet was set down and forks removed from the pallet, a nail punctured the bottom of the bottom cube that was Ieaning off the pallet edge. To stop the spill, the cubes above the bottom layer were removed from the pallet so the Ieaking cube could be inverted. Warehouse personnel cleaned up the spill with a nearby spill kit. column168: THIS SPILL OCCURRED DURING THE SORT. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURE OCCURRED. INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS A METAL PAINT CAN AND SOME BUBBLE WRAP. IT CONTAINED PRODUCT MICRON CSC GREEN PAINT. THE MANUFACTURER’S SAFETY DATA SHEET (SDS) LISTS A FLASH POINT OF 27 DEGREES CELCIUS/80 DEGREES FARENHEIT WHICH IS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID PER THE IATA/ICAO DG REGULATIONS. SECTION 14 OF THE SDS CLASSIFIES THIS PRODUCT AS UN 1263, PAINT, CLASS 3, PACKING GROUP III. AS THE SHIPPER DID NOT OFFER THE SHIPMENT WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, DG LABELS, NOR A SHIPPER’S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS FORM, IT IS UNDECLARED/HIDDEN DG. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED VIA EMAIL AND PHOTOS SENT. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

DURING THE PM SORT OPERATIONS AT THE FEDEX EXPRESS SORT FACILITY IN DES MOINES, IA A PLASTIC DRUM WA IDENTIFIED CONTAINING UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. FURTHER INVESTIGATION INDICATED THE DRUM CONTAINED CORTEVA GF5042, WHICH PER THE ASSOCIATED SDS IS FULLY REGULATED DANGEROUS GOODS AS UN3082 ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE N.O.S TECHNICAL NAME TOPRAMEZONE PG III. NONE OF THE INNER CONTENTS LEAKED OUT. THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKING OR LABELS ON THE PACKAGING, AND NO SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WAS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE INVOLVED PACKAGE IS BEING HELD PENDING FURTHER DISPOSITION.

column168: TWO SEPARATE SHIPMENTS CONSISITING OF 3 TOTAL PACKAGES (272295170422, 272295170433, 272295223040) WERE OFFERED OVER THE COUNTER TO A FEDEX LOCATION LOCATED IN DENVER COLORADO. ALL PACKAGES WERE DESTINED FOR THE SAME CONSIGNEE. AS THE PACKAGES WERE BEING LOADED INTO A CONTAINER, CYLINDERS WERE HEARD INSIDE BOX AND CAUSED SUSPICION. PACKAGES WERE OPENED AND AND IT WAS SEEN THAT EACH BOX CONTAINED A GAS CYLINDER. CUSTOMER CONFIRMED CYLINDER CONTAINED FOOD GRADE UN 1070 INSIDE OF CONTAINERS USED FOR BUSINESS, HOWEVER DID NOT UNDERSTAND HOW THIS WAS A DANGEROUS GOOD. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS NOR LABELS ON THE PACKAGES TO INDICATE DANGEROUS GOOD WERE INSIDE OF THE BOXES. BOXES APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN REUSED MULTIPLE TIMES. PACKAGES HAVE BEEN HELD AT LOCATION PENDING INVESTIGATION.
